The following is a list of mountains that have been presumed, at one time, to be the highest mountain in the world. How general were the following presumptions is unclear. Before the [[age of exploration]], no geographer could make any plausible assumption.

* [[Chimborazo (volcano)|Chimborazo]], {{convert|6267|m|ft|0}}. Presumed highest from sixteenth century until the beginning of  the 19th century. Not in the top 100 highest mountains when measured from sea level, however due to the earth's [[equatorial bulge]] this is the farthest point from the Earth's center.
* [[Nanda Devi]], {{convert|7816|m|ft|0}}. Presumed highest in the world before Kangchenjunga was sighted in an era when [[Nepal]] was still closed to the outside world. Now known to be the 23rd highest mountain in the world.
* [[Dhaulagiri]], {{convert|8167|m|ft|0}}. Presumed highest from 1808<ref>{{cite book|last=Waller |first=Derek J.|title=The Pundits: British Exploration of Tibet and Central Asia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PYqWhpyoQsoC&pg=PA174|date=2004 |publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0813191009|page=174}}</ref> until 1847.<ref name="mountainranges" /> Now known to be the 7th highest mountain in the world.
* [[Kangchenjunga]], {{convert|8586|m|ft|0}}. Presumed highest from 1847 until 1852. Now known to be the 3rd highest mountain in the world.<ref name="mountainranges">{{cite web|url=http://imagingeverest.rgs.org/Concepts/Virtual_Everest/-288.html|title=The Highest Mountain in the World|authorlink=www.johnkeay.com/|year=2003|website=Imaging Everest|publisher=The Royal Geographical Society (with the Institute of British Geographers)|isbn=9780743243865|ref=Excerpt from the book: Everest, Summit of Achievement|last1=Keay|first1=John|accessdate=May 12, 2016}}</ref>
* [[Mount Everest]], {{convert|8848|m|ft|0}}. Established as highest in 1852 and officially confirmed in 1856.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wrcOAAAAQAAJ&dq=%22tallest%20mountain%22&pg=PA574#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The tallest mountain in the world|date=6 October 1856|work=Allen's Indian Mail|page=574|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>
* [[K2]], {{convert|8611|m|ft|0}}. Discovered in 1856 before Mt. Everest was officially confirmed, K2's elevation became something of an enigma until it was officially resolved at a later date.<ref name="mountainranges" /> News media reported in 1986 that satellite measurements by the [[University of Washington]] during an expedition to K2 by George Wallenstein had given a height between {{convert|29064|ft|m}} and {{convert|29228|ft|m}}.<ref name="straightdope">{{cite web|url=http://www.straightdope.com/columns/read/1467/which-is-taller-mt-everest-or-k2|title=Which is taller, Mt. Everest or K2?|author=Ian|work=[[The Straight Dope]]|accessdate=6 September 2013}}</ref> This erroneous figure was quickly retracted, and K2's status as second highest was reaffirmed.<ref name="straightdope" />

