The steep Donga Range separates [[Bumthang District|Bumthang]] and [[Lhuentse District]]s and forms the watershed between the [[Raidāk River|Raidāk]] and [[Manas River]] systems. Northeastern portions of the Donga are known as Kurtoe (modern [[Kurtoe Gewog]], historical [[Kurtoed Province]]). [[Thrumshing La]] pass, also called Donga Pass, provides the only road access across the Donga Range at {{convert|3,787|m|ft}}.<ref name=Imperial/><ref name=Karan/> The steep Rodang La further north provides non-motor communication, and several southerly passes including Thebong La are used by herders.<ref name=LP/>{{rp|84}} <ref name=Karan/> At {{convert|20,965|ft|m}}, a major peak stands over Thrumshing La.<ref name=Imperial/><ref name=Karan/>

To the east runs another lesser spur of mountains separating [[Lhuentse Valley|Lhuentse]] and [[Trashiyangse Valley]]s.<ref name=LP/>{{rp|84}}

===Tawang Range===
To the east of the [[Manas River]] system, the Tawang Range (also called Kollong)<ref name=Imperial/> forms the eastern boundary of Bhutan.<ref name=HKB/> The Tawang Range originates in [[Tibet]], to the northeast of [[Arunachal Pradesh]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=A Contribution to the Flora of Bhutan |first1=D. B |last1=Deb |first2=G. Sen |last2=Gupta |first3=K. C |last3=Malick |journal=Bulletin of the Botanical Society of Bengal |volume=22 |publisher=Botanical Society of Bengal |year=1968 |page=170 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wDxBAAAAYAAJ |accessdate=2011-12-05}}</ref>

